    "created_at": "2015-07-26T12:33:14Z",
    "updated_at": "2015-07-26T12:38:43Z",
    "body": "@Godisemo \n\n> Just a few examples when arbitrary sized pdf would be necessary:\n> \n> If you use something like reveal.js for creating presentations you might want to export pdf files sized to fit the screen.\n> To create vector images that can be included in pdf files created by typesetting programs like latex.\n\nThanks for the explaination. \n\n> I played a little with this last night by trying to adjust sizes in atom/browser/api/lib/web-contents.coffee but I had trouble converting pixel dimensions to metric dimensions. \n\nActually, you can specify the generated pdf page size by customizing the `mediaSize` in `web-contens.coffee`. But as was mentioned before, the `print` API is not designed for such usage, and Chromium doesn't expose such interfaces neither. I'm not sure whether there is a side-effect on customizing the page size.\n\n> but I had trouble converting pixel dimensions to metric dimensions.\n\nYou can do the convert as follows, assuming that the screen height dpi is the same with width's, represents by `DPI`:\n- The height of pdf in microns: `window.height()*25.4/DPI` \\* 1000\n- The width of pdf in microns: `window.width()*25.4/DPI` \\* 1000\n\n> Is there any reference or documentation available for it?\n\nUnfortunatelly, Chromium org doesn't provide any document on the print API implementation.  If you have to do it, reading the code is the only way.\n"
  },
